        <div class="col-lg-8">
            <h1>
                Getting Started with Github
            </h1>
            <p>Embarking on your GitHub journey opens a world of collaborative software development, version control, and community engagement. To get started, visit github.com and sign up for an account if you haven't already. Once registered, familiarize yourself with the platform's interface, focusing on key features such as repositories, branches, commits, and pull requests. Creating a new repository is the first step: think of it as a project folder where your code and related files reside. You can initialize it with a README file, which serves as an introduction to your project. As you begin to explore GitHub's functionalities, you'll learn to clone repositories to your local machine, allowing for offline work, and push changes back to GitHub, ensuring your project remains up-to-date. Engaging with the GitHub community by exploring public repositories, contributing to open-source projects, and collaborating with other developers will enrich your understanding and enhance your coding skills. GitHub not only offers a robust version control system but also fosters a collaborative environment where innovation thrives.</p>
            <!-- Featured blog post-->
            <div class="card mb-4">
            <div class="card-body">
                <main class="container">
                    <section>
                        <h3>How to Use GitHub Pages</h3>
                        <h5>Step-1: Create a GitHub Repository</h5>
                        <ol>

                            <li>
                                <b> <p>Sign in to GitHub:</b> If you don’t have an account, create one at <a href="how-to-create-github-account.html" alt="Create Github Account">Github Account Creation Guide.</a></p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <b>Create a New Repository:</b>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Click on the <b>“+” </b>icon in the top-right corner and select <b>“New repository.”</b></li>
                                    <img src="https://docs.github.com/assets/cb-29762/mw-1440/images/help/repository/repo-create-global-nav-update.webp" alt="New Repo image" width="350" height="250">
                                    <li>Name your repository following the format <username>.github.io (e.g., johndoe.github.io). This format is essential for user and organization pages.</li>
                                    <img src="https://docs.github.com/assets/cb-48480/mw-1440/images/help/pages/create-repository-name-pages.webp" alt="New Repo image" width="600" height="150">
                                    <li>Set the repository to <b>"Public."</b></li>
                                    <li>Optionally, initialize the repository with a README file.</li>
                                    <li>Click <b>"Create repository."</b></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </section>
                    <section>
                        <h5>Step-2: Setup Your Website</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <li><strong>Clone the Repository</strong></li>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Clone the repository to your local machine using Git.
                                    <img src="learn.csedge.courses-main/Images/CloneRepo.png" alt="Clone repo">
                                </li>
                                <code>git clone https://github.com/<b>username/username</b>.github.io</br>
                                cd <b>username</b>.github.io</code>
                            </ul>
                            <li><strong>Create Your Site</strong></li>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Start with a simple HTML file. Create an index.html file:
                                </li>
                                <code><strong>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</code></br>
                                <code>&lt;html&gt;</code></br>
                                    <code>&lt;head&gt;</code></br>
                                        <code>&lt;title&gt;</strong></code>My GitHub Pages Site. <code><strong>&lt;/title&gt;</code></br>
                                    <code>&lt;/head&gt;</code></br>
                                    <code>&lt;body&gt;</code></br>
                                <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></strong>Welcome to My GitHub Pages Site!<code><strong>&lt;/h1&gt;</code></br>
                                <code> &lt;p&gt;</code></strong>This is a simple static site hosted on GitHub Pages.<code><strong>&lt;/p&gt;</code></br>
                                        <code>&lt;/body&gt;</code></br>
                                            <code> &lt;/html&gt;</code></br>
                                        </strong> </code></br>

                                <li>Save the file and add it to your repository.</li>
                                <code>git add <b>index.html</b><br></code>
                                <code>git commit -m <strong>"Initial commit"</strong><br></code>
                                <code>git push origin main<br></code>
                                <img src="learn.csedge.courses-main/Images/saveRepo.png" alt="SaveRepository">
                            </ul>
                        </ol>
                    </section>
                    <section>
                        <h5>Step-3: Enable GitHub Pages</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <strong><li>Navigate to Repository Settings:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Go to your repository on GitHub and click on the "Settings" tab.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                                <strong><li>Enable GitHub Pages:</li></strong>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        Scroll down to the "GitHub Pages" section.
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        In the "Source" section, select the branch you want to use (typically 'main').
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        Click "Save."
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            <strong><li>Access Your Site:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>After a few minutes, your site should be live at <b>`https://&lt;username&gt;.github.io`.</b></li>
                            </ul>
                        </ol>
                    </section>



                    <section>
                        <h5>Step-4: Customize Your Site</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <strong><li>Using Jekyll:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    GitHub Pages supports Jekyll, allowing you to use templates and markdown files to generate your site.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Create a <b>`_config.yml`</b> file to configure your Jekyll site. Here's an example configuration.
                                </li>
                                <code><b>title:</b> My GitHub Pages Site<br></code>
                                <code><b>description:</b> A simple site hosted with GitHub Pages</strong><br></code>
                                <code><b>theme:</b> minima<br><br></code>
                                <img src="posts/images/config.png" alt="configfile">
                            </ul>
                            <strong><li>Add Content:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Create a <B>`_posts`</B> directory to add blog posts (if using Jekyll).<br>
                                    <img src="posts/images/posts.png" alt="postsfile">
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Each post should follow the naming convention YYYY-MM-DD-title.md and contain front matter. <br>Example:<br>
                                </li>
                                <code>---<br></code>
                                <code>layout: post<br></code>
                                <code>title: "First Blog Post"<br></code>
                                <code>date: 2024-05-01<br></code>
                                <code>---<br></code>
                                <code>Welcome to my first blog post on GitHub Pages!<br></code>
                            </ul>
                            <strong><li>Commit and Push Changes:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>After adding your content and configuration files, commit and push your changes:</b></li>
                                <code>git add .</code>
                                <code>git commit -m <b>"Add Jekyll configuration and first post"</b><br></code>
                                <code>git push origin main .<br><br></code>
                                <img src="posts/images/commit file.png" alt="commitss">
                            </ul>
                        </ol>
                    </section>
                    <section>
                        <h5>Step-5: Further Customization and Maintenance</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <strong><li>Themes and Plugins:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Explore available Jekyll themes to change the look and feel of your site. You can find themes at Jekyll Themes.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Add plugins to extend Jekyll's functionality. For example, adding SEO, sitemap generation, or analytics.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                            <strong><li>Custom Domain:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    If you want to use a custom domain, you can set this up in the "Custom domain" section under the GitHub Pages settings of your repository.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Update your DNS settings with your domain registrar to point to GitHub Pages.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                            <strong><li>Continuous Updates:</li></strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    Regularly update your site by committing new content, updates, and bug fixes. GitHub Actions can be set up to automate builds and deployments if you're using advanced features.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </ol>
                    </section>
                    <section>
                        <h3>Conclusion</h3>
                        <p>GitHub Pages is an exceptional tool for anyone looking to host a static website for free. It combines the power of GitHub's version control with the simplicity of static site generation, making it ideal for both seasoned developers and newcomers alike. By following the detailed steps outlined in this guide, you can create, customize, and maintain your own GitHub Pages site, providing a professional online presence with minimal hassle.
                            <br>Get started with GitHub Pages today and showcase your projects, portfolio, or blog to the world effortlessly!</p>
                    </section>
                </main>
            </div>
            </div>
